<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:302px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Olber%27s_Paradox_-_All_Points.gif" class="image" title="Olbers' paradox in action"><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/d/d2/Olber%27s_Paradox_-_All_Points.gif" width="300" height="300" border="0" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Olber%27s_Paradox_-_All_Points.gif" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="/skins-1.5/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
Olbers' paradox in action</div>
</div>
</div>
<p><b>Olbers' paradox</b>, is the argument that the darkness of the night sky conflicts with the supposition of an infinite and eternal <a href="/wiki/Static_universe" title="Static universe">static universe</a>. It was described by the <a href="/wiki/Germany" title="Germany">German</a> <a href="/wiki/Astronomer" title="Astronomer">astronomer</a> <a href="/wiki/Heinrich_Wilhelm_Olbers" title="Heinrich Wilhelm Olbers" class="mw-redirect">Heinrich Wilhelm Olbers</a> in 1823 (but not published until 1826 by <a href="/wiki/Johann_Elert_Bode" title="Johann Elert Bode">Bode</a>) and earlier by <a href="/wiki/Johannes_Kepler" title="Johannes Kepler">Johannes Kepler</a> in 1610 and <a href="/wiki/Edmond_Halley" title="Edmond Halley">Halley</a> and <a href="/wiki/Jean-Philippe_de_Cheseaux" title="Jean-Philippe de Cheseaux">Cheseaux</a> in the 18th century. It is one of the pieces of evidence for a non-static universe such as the current <a href="/wiki/Lambda-CDM_model" title="Lambda-CDM model">Big Bang model</a>. This "paradox" is sometimes also known as the "<b>dark night sky paradox</b>" (see <a href="/wiki/Physical_paradox" title="Physical paradox">physical paradox</a>).</p>
